|ABOUT EXPLANATION1|
————————————————————
• Pre-processor Macros
 ——————————————————————
~ I implemented Macros to maximize execution speed and maintain memory efficiency. While they require "correct" implementation to avoid side effects, they provide the low-level performance needed for real-time mobile rendering.

• "Thermal" Source Initialization (The "Fuel")
 ——————————————————————————————————————————–———
~ The first loop manages Heat Generation. Using mathematical randomization, it simulates a "fuel" source at the bottom of the buffer. This "fuel" provides the initial energy required for the fire to propagate upward, acting as the foundation of the thermal system.

• Propagation & Displacement Logic (UP1, UP2)
 ——————————————————————————————————————————–––
~ The second loop handles Fluid Dynamics. It dictates the upward movement of heat pixels, including:
Directional Physics: Controlling how the flame sways.
Heat Transfer: Simulating how "soldiers" (pixels) carry thermal data from the source to the upper atmosphere of the simulation.

• Discrete Gradient System (Gradi)
 ——————————————————————————————————
~ For the visual output, I opted for a Discrete Color Gradient (Blue-themed) rather than a smooth procedural gradient. This was a strategic decision to prevent system overhead and ensure the simulation remains stable on mobile hardware without causing thermal throttling or UI freezing.

Note: The codebase utilizes optimized macros. They are structured to be highly efficient while remaining human-readable.



ABOUT EXPLANATION2 

The simulation utilizes a heat scale ranging from 0 to 30. The system dynamically maps character density to heat intensity: lower values render 'thinner' characters to represent cooler embers, while higher values trigger 'thicker' characters for intense flames.

